    "rich_text_bJjUfk": {
      "type": "rich-text",
      "blocks": {
        "heading_FMBJUK": {
          "type": "heading",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "<strong>Part 2: The Real Costs of a Broken Integration</strong>",
            "heading_size": "h1"
          }
        },
        "text_yBnmbV": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>The sticker shock from budget overruns is just the beginning. The real-world consequences of a failed integration are far more damaging, impacting every corner of your business. These aren't just IT problems; they are business-crippling events that can halt your growth.</p><ul><li><strong>Financial Impact.</strong> Overruns are common. In Panorama’s ERP Report, <strong>41% of organizations reported going over budget (32.1% slightly, 9.3% significantly)</strong> on their ERP initiative.[5] Over‑customization is a known cost driver; research recommends quantifying customization decisions early because they materially affect effort and risk.[6] Hidden costs (integration, data quality remediation, change management) are frequently underestimated.[7]</li></ul><p></p><ul><li>Inventory inaccuracies alone carry measurable revenue impact. Retail studies estimate <strong>~4% sales loss from stockouts</strong> and show that <strong>improving inventory record accuracy can lift sales by ~4–8%</strong> — a useful proxy for the business cost of poor data synchronization.[8][9]</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Operational Impact.</strong> When data can’t be trusted, teams revert to manual reconciliation and workarounds, extending cycle times. Benchmarks show the order‑to‑cash process is highly sensitive to manual steps; APQC tracks end‑to‑end O2C cycle time and highlights the operational cost of delays.[10] Manual single‑entry workflows introduce <strong>measurable error rates</strong>, with peer‑reviewed studies showing <strong>per‑field error rates ranging from ~0.5% to 6.5%</strong> and strong evidence that <strong>double‑entry significantly reduces errors</strong>.[11][12]</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Customer Impact.</strong> Poor integrations degrade basic buyer expectations (accurate availability, order tracking, delivery dates). In B2B, <strong>86% of buyers are willing to switch if another web store offers a better experience</strong>, according to a recent survey reported by Digital Commerce 360 (and echoed in trade coverage).[13][14]</li></ul>"
          }
        }
      },
